===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `tail` baraye namayesh dadane akharin khat-ha-ye yek file estefade mishavad. Be tore pishfarz, 10 khat az akhar file ra neshan midahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `tail -n <tedad>` --> 🔢  Namayesh dadane `tedad` khat az akhar file. Misal: `tail -n 20 file.txt` 20 khat akhar file.txt ra neshon midahad.
    🔹 `tail -f file`    --> 🔄  Negah dashtane baz boodane file va namayesh dadane har taghirati ke dar file ijad shavad. Baraye monitor kardane log file-ha mofid ast.
    🔹 `tail +<shomare>` --> ➕  Namayesh dadane file az khat-e `shomare` be baad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ tail myfile.txt

    🔹 Namayesh 10 khat akhar file `myfile.txt`.

    $ tail -f logfile.log

    🔹 Monitor kardane taghirat dar file `logfile.log` be tore real-time.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ tail -n 5 data.txt

    🔹 Faghat 5 khat akhar file `data.txt` ra neshon midahad. Agar `data.txt` kamtar az 5 khat dashte bashad, hameye khat-ha ra neshon midahad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `tail` command displays the last lines of a file. By default, it shows the last 10 lines.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `tail -n <number>` --> 🔢 Display `number` lines from the end of the file.  Example: `tail -n 20 file.txt` shows the last 20 lines of file.txt.
    🔹 `tail -f file`    --> 🔄 Keep the file open and display any changes made to it. Useful for monitoring log files.
    🔹 `tail +<number>` --> ➕ Display the file from line `number` onwards.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ tail myfile.txt

    🔹 Display the last 10 lines of the file `myfile.txt`.

    $ tail -f logfile.log

    🔹 Monitor changes in the file `logfile.log` in real-time.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ tail -n 5 data.txt

    🔹 Only the last 5 lines of the `data.txt` file are shown. If `data.txt` has fewer than 5 lines, it shows all the lines.